lops a fundamentally new theory of democratic participation termed "ocular democracy«, emphasizing the citizens' view as an instrument of democratic control that does not focus on contents but rather on the public performance of leading politicians. Presenting that theory about democracy, this volume makes its approach as well as the debate about it accessible to the German context of discourse for the first time. The contributors take up the debate about the crisis of representative democracy and examine the potential a plebiscitary democracy of viewers may have.  afunded by Forschungsinstitut für Philosophie Hannover  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aPolitical participation. 4aDemokratietheorie. 4aJeffrey Green. 4aOkulare Demokratie. 4aPlebiszit. 4aPolitics. 4aPolitik. 4aPolitikwissenschaft. 4aPolitische Theorie. 4aRepräsentation. 4aTeilhabe. 4aÄsthetik. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aJeffrey Green.  aParticipation.  aPlebiscitarianism.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitical Theory.  aPolitics.  aRepresentation.  aTheories of Democracy.1 aBrodocz, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFruhstorfer, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerlsbeck, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Jeffrey Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Dominik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Dominik, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt